<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Fall in US drink sales hits GrandMet: International food
group keeps its options open on the future of struggling IEL joint venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Grand Metropolitan, the international drinks and food giant, fell
26p to 457p yesterday as the group disclosed that de-stocking in the US
drinks market was likely to cost it Pounds 40m this year. The group also
dashed hopes of immediate disentanglement from its struggling Inntrepreneur
Estates (IEL) joint venture with Courage, saying only that it was 'studying
a range of options'. IEL, Britain's biggest pub operator, broke even in the
half compared with a loss of Pounds 12m last year.
Group pre-tax profits were up 10 per cent at Pounds 446m, in line with
expectations.
Mr George Bull, chief executive, said the revival of the US economy had
prompted GrandMet's IDV drinks subsidiary to stock up last autumn in the
hope of increased sales. In fact, the market had fallen 3 per cent and IDV's
sales by 2 per cent. At the same time, IDV had tackled overstocking problems
caused by concentration among US drinks wholesalers. 'We decided that now
was the moment to grab the nettle,' Mr Bull said. Half the cost had been
incurred in the first half, with the balance to come in the second.
IDV's worldwide operating profit fell 2 per cent to Pounds 254m, with an 18
per cent rise in North America offset by a 13 per cent fall in the rest of
the world. The North American increase was almost wholly due to a one-off
payment of around Pounds 17m on the termination of US distribution rights
for Absolut vodka.
GrandMet said IDV's longer-term prospects were better than at any time in
the past decade. 'The market we're selling in has the capacity to double.
China and India alone are providing 500m new drinkers who weren't available
to us two years ago,' said Mr Bull.
Operating profit in food manufacture rose 6 per cent to Pounds 147m, with a
19 per cent increase in North America while Europe fell into a Pounds 3m
loss, from Pounds 1m profit. Mr Bull said the improvement in the US was
strategically very important. 'We've done a lot of work straightening it
out, and it's now starting to pay off.'
Profits at the Burger King hamburger chain were up 16 per cent, with 244 new
restaurants opened and 5 per cent volume growth in existing outlets.
The Pearle opticians chain broke even, after a Pounds 2m loss. GrandMet
aimed to return the business to modest profit, then sell it.
The tax charge fell from 32.4 per cent to 29.2 per cent. Mr Gerald Corbett,
finance director, said restructuring of group borrowings to take advantage
of tax losses would cut the tax charge by some Pounds 30m this year and for
three or four years thereafter. Lower tax helped earnings per share to rise
15 per cent to 15.0p before exceptionals. The dividend was raised 6.2 per
cent to 5.15p.
Free cashflow was Pounds 232m (Pounds 95m), due largely to falls in working
capital, interest charges and capital expenditure. Net borrowings were
Pounds 2.4bn down Pounds 460m. This reduced gearing from 83 per cent to 62
per cent including intangibles. Sir Allen Sheppard, chairman, said funds
from cashflow and disposals would be spent on add-on acquisitions in branded
food and drink, on which GrandMet had already spent Pounds 350m in the half
year.
Lex, Page 18; IEL, Page 21; Market, Page 38
</TEXT>
