FT  13 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yet another Friday night when the best advice is to stay away from the
television ..unless your idea of a good time is watching Danny Baker ask
whether Arthur Lowe appeared in adverts for Trillions sweets or Hanky Panky
popcorn. That, we are promised (all right, threatened) is the sort of
question in which the new quiz Bygones will specialise. Is this part of the
BBC's drive towards the 'Himalayan option', the domination of the high
ground of broadcasting? (7.00 BBC1). You might have hoped that Europe
Express would be television's version of Christopher Booker's hair-raising
column in the Sunday Telegraph, detailing the demented bureaucratic
taradiddle which, week by week, reduces the quality of life in Britain, in
the name of a united Europe. But no. It is a series of tabloid interviews,
this week including singer Mari Boine who is 'set to' take Europe by storm
(8.00 Channel 4). The oddest billing of the night is on Radio 3 in the
'Friday Feature', L'Homme Arme, presented by Jeremy Beadle who traces the
history of a famous medieval song (10.45).
