<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Local traders criticise charities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Federation of Small Busi-nesses called yesterday for an investigation by
the Office of Fair Trading into 'exploitative practices' by hospitals,
charities, schools and churches, Richard Gourlay writes.
The federation, which represents 50,000 small businesses, says established
enterprises are 'trading in a jungle of unfair competition'.
It adds that charity shops sell new goods while enjoying lower rates than
commercial businesses; churches have rate-exempt premises that they can let
to commercial businesses which then profit from subsidised rentals; and
schools compete directly with private-sector suppliers of accom-modation,
hotels and caterers.
The report also attacks the 'increasing abuse' of car boot sales and
itinerant markets. 'Legitimate local traders and licensed market traders are
being undercut and undermined,' the federation says.
</TEXT>
