<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Sizewell B ahead of budget target and on schedule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sizewell B in Suffolk, Britain's first pressurised water reactor nuclear
power station, is heading for completion more than Pounds 100m below the
budget set five years ago.
It is expected to be commissioned several months ahead of the February 1995
commitment given to government before construction began in 1987.
Completion of the plant on time and below its estimated Pounds 2.03bn budget
follows delays and large cost overruns during the 1970s and 1980s in the
building of advanced gas-cooled reactors.
The causes were late design changes and industrial disputes which led to a
loss of more than 11m man-hours.
Dungeness B in Kent took 18 years to complete - 13 more than scheduled  -
and at double the cost.
Sizewell B's budget was set in 1989. Previous estimates had been lower, but
Nuclear Electric, the plant owner, says the rise from the most recent figure
of Pounds 1.87bn was due to the government abandoning plans for four power
stations of the same design and the consequent loss in economies of scale.
Nuclear Electric hopes to start generating electricity by August or
September.
A further delay is possible because Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Pollution
has yet to issue a licence for the plant to discharge radioactivity
routinely.
While construction is within the timetable given to the government, work is
several weeks behind the company's hopes of last year that it would
commission in May or June.
With only weeks to go before the scheduled completion of construction
contracts, officials expect the capital cost to be in the region of Pounds
1.9bn.
Final figures will be passed to the Department of Trade and Industry, which
is examining the company's planning application for a Pounds 3.5bn
twin-reactor, Sizewell C.
A go-ahead for this plant depends on the outcome of a public inquiry and
also the government's long-awaited nuclear power review. The timetable for
the review and its remit have yet to be announced.
Nuclear Electric already has planning permission for a single reactor at
Hinkley Point C in Somerset but construction there is also subject to a
favourable review out-come.
</TEXT>
