<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Insurers warned of takeover threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, has urged insurance
companies to do more to protect themselves against the threat of hostile
takeovers.
Merger and acquisition activity was likely to increase again as Europe came
out of the recession, Mr Heseltine told a dinner of the Association of
British Insurers.
'You should be taking steps now to protect yourselves, in the same way that
your competitors are already protected,' he said in a speech that examined
the international competitiveness of the UK insurance industry.
He said insurers faced new challenges, and moves were needed 'that will
enable you to stand against that cold wind which is blowing across the
globalised market'.
Mr Heseltine's remarks follow a recent 'Swot' (strengths, weaknesses,
opportunities and threats) analysis of the industry by the Department of
Trade and Industry.
Although the UK insurers had strong products and systems, and a well
regarded system of regulation, the quality of some of their underwriting had
been poor. Also, Mr Heseltine said insurers' costs were still too high in
some areas.
In addition, concerns about 'mis-selling' in life insurance and in some
other areas had created an 'image problem'.
Threats facing the industry included the trend towards self-insurance by
many buyers, technological and judicial inflation and the adequacy of
reinsurance.
In the life sector, insurers faced competition from unit trusts and
deposit-based products.
Mr Heseltine called for a dialogue with the industry but warned that the
department was not about to become 'a soft touch'.
He had been particularly disappointed that it had taken so long to persuade
the industry to come up with supporters for the DTI competitiveness
strategy, although he said that three individuals were about to join.
</TEXT>
