<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Tax hopes for staff insurance premiums: New Inland Revenue
proposals go to consultation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Directors and employees would no longer be taxed on insurance premiums paid
by their companies under proposals unveiled by the Inland Revenue yesterday.
Taxpayers would also be able to seek rulings from the Revenue on the tax
treatment of transactions before they submit their annual returns, according
to details in a separate wide-ranging consultation document issued
yesterday.
The first Revenue document considers extending tax relief on some or all
areas of risk covered by directors' and officers' (D &amp; O) insurance
policies.
The proposals are topical at a time when there is growing litigation against
directors and others in connection with corporate collapses in the wake of
the recession.
At present, any such premiums paid by companies are taxable as a benefit in
kind. The Revenue estimates that providing full relief would cost about
Pounds 5m a year.
The idea was raised by Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the
Treasury, in the finance bill debate in March.
The Revenue said yesterday that if the consultation exercise suggested the
need for reform, the changes could be proposed in November in time for the
next finance bill.
The document questions whether all risks covered by D &amp; O policies - such as
breach of trust or duty, neglect, error and mis-statement - should be
eligible for relief.
It suggests tax relief might also be extended to cover the costs of the
defence of those charged and acquitted of fraud, dishonesty and malicious
conduct, which are not normally covered by insurance policies.
It proposes extending the tax reliefs to premiums paid by directors and
officers themselves, as well as those paid by their companies - which it
estimates as negligible.
It also suggests exemptions to meet uninsured liabilities by directors and
employees, which it says might very tentatively amount to Pounds 30m a year.
The second consultative document issued yesterday proposes details of a
system for 'pre-return rulings' for income, corporation and capital gains
tax.
It followed an announcement of the idea by Mr Dorrell at the annual dinner
the previous evening of the Association of Her Majesty's Inspectors of Taxes
and Senior Revenue Officials.
The Revenue said that taxpayers would be able to apply after a transaction
but before filing their tax return to obtain a ruling on how it should be
assessed for tax.
In exchange for a fee reflecting the cost of the service, they would also be
able to seek guidance on tax treatment before they undertook a transaction.
The idea ties in with the move towards self-assessment on personal income
tax and pay and file by companies.
Comments on the insurance document are due by June 23 this year and on the
pre-rulings document by July 18.
</TEXT>
