<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Chairman of Welsh agency resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, WaleS and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chairman of a government-funded Welsh development agency has resigned in
response to a critical report published yesterday by the Commons public
accounts committee.
In the latest embarrassment for Welsh quangos, the committee condemned a
housing policy and car leasing scheme run by the Development Board for Rural
Wales. Mr Glyn Davies, the agency's chairman, said in his resignation
letter: 'I hope this action will enable the DBRW to recover from any
damaging effect resulting from external criticisms.'
The board, which has 120 staff and a grant this year of nearly Pounds 17m,
had illegally allocated houses under two sets of rules, one published and
the other unpublished. Its housing officer and his ex-wife were housed under
the unpublished rules when they would not have otherwise qualified.
'It was wholly unacceptable,' the MPs said, 'for any public authority to
publish a policy for the information of the public and then operate on a
totally different basis.'
It reflected badly on all concerned that for 13 years no one appeared to
realise the DBRW was failing to comply with the housing acts. It was also
unacceptable that a car leasing scheme had been amended without consulting
the Welsh Office.
The MPs said they 'were very surprised that, given the nature and scale of
maladministration' the board had decided not to take disciplinary action.
Accepting Mr Davies' resignation, Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, said the
board had made a significant contribution to the economic and social
development of mid-Wales. 'I do, however, entirely understand your wish in
the light of recent events that public confidence in the board should be
quickly restored.' Mr Redwood is already reviewing the DBRW's future and it
is expected it may be subsumed into the Welsh Development Agency.
Mr Davies, who had been chairman for seven years, said he also resigned his
membership of the WDA, Wales Tourist Board and Welsh Economic Council.
The Commons committee last year strongly censured the WDA.
</TEXT>
