<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / CrossRail decision defended by MP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative chairman of the four-man committee of MPs which turned down
proposals for the Pounds 2bn London CrossRail proposal yesterday launched a
defence of its surprise decision.
Mr Tony Marlow said the main factors in the committee's thinking were the
decline in commuter travel since the line was planned in 1989, and competing
transport developments elsewhere in London such as the Jubilee Line.
'We were there for 30 detailed, meticulous days, cross-examining the
promoters more thoroughly than any previous committee had done,' Mr Marlow
said. 'I started out well disposed. It is an exciting, imaginative scheme
but we did listen to the detailed evidence.'
The committee concluded that no private-sector company would be willing to
take the risk of financing the pro-ject.
Mr Marlow doubted that the government would be able to ask the committee to
reconsider its verdict as had been suggested by the Labour party. This would
require the government to show that the committee had acted outside the
procedural rules or that there had been a material change in its
circumstances.
In a separate development, one expert close to the project said that in
spite of the political support for rescuing the project, transport officials
were secretly pleased it had been rejected.
The economic case for building CrossRail was 'farcical', he said, and would
require traffic growth during the next 15 years equivalent to the high rates
achieved for only 18 months during the 1980s boom to justify building it.
</TEXT>
