<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Blair emerges as the candidate Tories fear most
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs acknowledged yesterday that there were at least six serious candidates
for the leadership of the Labour party, and that in such circumstances the
prospects of avoiding a damaging and public tussle between leading figures
from its modernising and traditionalist wings did not look good.
In the atmosphere of stunned disbelief pervading Westminster, few MPs were
ready to talk openly about the succession contest that will culminate this
autumn at the latest.
The front runner - and the one most feared by the Tories - is Mr Tony Blair,
the urbane, Oxford-educated lawyer who has made a good fist of shadowing Mr
Michael Howard in the high-profile home affairs portfolio.
Mr Blair, a leading moderniser, has succeeded in chipping away at the
Conservative party's traditionally unassailable position as the party of law
and order by portraying Labour as being tougher on crime and the causes of
crime.
His fluency and ready smile make him arguably the most impressive Labour
performer on the electronic media. There were suggestions yesterday that he
is also the moderniser with whom backbench traditionalists can most easily
live.
But Mr Blair must first convince supporters of Mr Gordon Brown, his
modernising colleague, that he and not the shadow chancellor has the better
chance of winning the race.
After years when the pair were virtually inseparable, Mr Brown has recently
fallen behind in the succession stakes, largely because of what some see as
a patchy performance as chief Treasury spokesman. Some MPs also see Mr
Blair, a family man, as a more rounded individual.
One leading traditionalist said that the strongest campaign at the moment
was a 'stop Gordon' campaign. Most Labour MPs think it inconceivable that
both Mr Brown and Mr Blair will decide to run.
But Mr Brown's closest advisers have yet to accept that their man has worse
prospects. Mr Brown outpolled Mr Blair by 18 votes in the last shadow
cabinet election.
The leading traditionalist candidate is expected to be Mr John Prescott, the
shadow employment secretary. His powerful speech at last year's party
conference played an important part in ensuring that Mr Smith won the tense
battle to inject greater democracy into Labour's links with the trade
unions.
The burly former transport spokesman would secure strong backing from the
union movement if he decided to run.
Many MPs are concerned however that a head-on clash between a leading
moderniser and a leading traditionalist would be extremely damaging for the
party. They hope that Mr Prescott could be persuaded to run only as deputy
leader.
Certainly, Mr Prescott's installation as deputy leader would be the minimum
price demanded by the Labour left in return for allowing a leading
moderniser an unhindered tilt at the leadership.
A strategy for such a balanced ticket would run aground if Mrs Margaret
Beckett, the deputy leader, decided not to run for leader. Many MPs believe
that she could secure her current post if she did this 'in the interests of
party unity'.
Many MPs expect that Mrs Beckett will run, however, in which case the
strength of her candidacy will largely depend on how she is seen to have
done as interim leader and on Labour's performance in the European
elections.
As a former stalwart of the left, Mrs Beckett could garner heavy support
from that wing and from women MPs.
Another potential candidate from the centre-left of the party is Mr Robin
Cook, the shadow trade and industry secretary, who topped the poll in the
most recent shadow cabinet election.
Mr Cook is widely regarded as the cleverest of Labour's leading politicians
and has shadowed Mr Michael Heseltine astutely and effectively. For some his
main disadvantage is his appearance, but he might emerge as a compromise
candidate with some appeal to both traditionalists and modernisers.
An outside bet to run is Mr Jack Cunningham, the shadow foreign secretary,
who could construct a platform as the 'continuity' candidate  - the man who
would carry on Mr Smith's good work.
However, he came within an ace of being voted out of the shadow cabinet last
autumn.
</TEXT>
