<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Loss transforms the political landscape: The death of John
Smith will make the Labour party's character the focus of attention
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Suddenly nothing is clear. The tragic death of John Smith has left the
Labour party facing a choice which is critical to the outcome of the next
general election. Amid the sadness which enveloped Westminster, Mr Smith's
colleagues sensed both a risk and an opportunity.
The shock waves from Mr Smith's death were not confined to the Labour party.
His departure has transformed the political landscape.
The genuine sorrow among senior Conservatives was followed quickly by the
judgment that Mr John Major's position was much more secure.
The focus of much political attention would, during the summer at least,
switch to the battle for the Labour leadership. Labour's campaign for the
European elections would be badly damaged. Mr Michael Heseltine, the victim
last year of a heart attack, was all of a sudden a much less attractive
rival to Mr Major.
Only hours before his fatal heart attack Mr Smith had been celebrating with
his colleagues at a glittering fund-raising dinner in London. Friends said
he was in sparkling form. His party was looking forward to following a
strong performance in this month's local elections with a decisive victory
in the European poll.
Consistently 20 points ahead of a government seemingly intent on
self-destruction, Labour had begun to persuade itself that after almost 15
years in the wilderness, power was at last within its grasp.
Even those among the party's modernisers who were occasionally frustrated by
Mr Smith's careful, cautious approach to remaking policies, were impressed
by his growing appeal to the electorate. MPs on the unreconstructed left saw
him as more radical than he was perceived of in the outside world. They were
impressed by his ability to fight them without rancour.
In an opinion poll a few weeks back nearly two-thirds of those questioned
said he would make a good prime minister. A Tory cabinet minister yesterday
offered the same judgment. The minister was not just being polite about the
dead.
But Mr Smith left unfinished the task of returning the Labour party to
electability. Mr Neil Kinnock's legacy after the 1992 general election was a
party which had dumped most of the ideological baggage it had carried
through the political wilderness, but had yet to rediscover an identity.
After the 1992 general election Mr Smith pressed on with reform. Tax and
spending pledges were quietly dropped, the leadership confronted the unions
over one-member-one-vote (Omov) in the system of elections for Labour
parliamentary candidates.
Mr Smith sketched out plans for radical constitutional reform. Mr Tony Blair
has fundamentally reshaped the party's attitude to crime and punishment. Mr
Gordon Brown has begun the slow, painful task of building a credible
economic strategy.
But the process has been slowing. The disarray in the Conservative party
removed the sense of urgency. Mr Smith made the strategic decision to defer
detailed policy commitments until the second half of this parliament. His
perilously narrow victory over the unions on Omov reminded him that
factionalism had not been banished from the Labour party.
So until yesterday morning the prevailing mood in the party at Westminster
was that it was probably enough to sit tight and wait for the Tories to lose
the general election.
If that was ever a realistic prospect - and the astute on the party's front
benches at Westminster never really believed it - Mr Smith's departure has
removed it. Labour now has to make a choice. It is one between advance and
retrenchment: between continuing on the path mapped out by Mr Kinnock from
socialism to social democracy or deciding to reclaim some of the party's
radical roots.
The choice will be posed starkly in the forthcoming leadership contest. Mr
Smith's colleagues were understandably reluctant yesterday to talk openly
about the succession. The formal contest anyway will be deferred until after
the European elections next month. But no one doubted who the contenders
would be.
Mr Blair and Mr Brown represent the modernising tendency. They want to
accelerate the process of reform, to recast Labour in the mould of its
social democrat counterparts in the rest of Europe.
Mr Blair is the favourite among MPs. He is just 41, but has displayed
formidable political talents. A public school boy, he has middle-class voter
appeal in southern England. MPs on the left of the party are less
antagonistic towards him than might be expected.
Mr Blair is judged by professionals to be the politician most likely to
return the party to power. In the bars and lobbies of Westminster, parallels
are already being drawn with the death of the then Labour leader Hugh
Gaitskell in 1963. It was the young moderniser Mr Harold Wilson who won the
succession and the subsequent general election.
However, Mr Brown has worked hard to win friends in the constituencies. He
should secure the backing of the powerful Scottish contingent of Labour MPs.
He has run a strong campaign against the government's tax increases. He
wants to be prime minister.
Labour though, remains equivocal about its future. In spite of nearly 15
years out of power, many in the party cannot break with an emotional
attachment to the past. No one believes any more in wholesale public
ownership. But the virtues of the market have not permeated deep into
Labour's consciousness.
On the many committees shaping policy for the next general election, the
modernisers are frequently confounded by the proponents of a more radical
socialism.
Mr John Prescott and Mr Robin Cook represent this still powerful strand of
opinion. Both have strong followings among party activists and trade
unionists. Both have many friends on the left at Westminster. Either could
win.
But for now the intricacies of the electoral system and the labyrinthine
nature of Labour politics make for far more 'ifs' and 'buts' than for
certainties.
Labour is still an unpredictable party. It will be days if not weeks before
the shape of the leadership contest emerges. But the choice will not go
away. The party must decide if it wants to govern.
</TEXT>
