<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Tributes flood in for a 'formidable opponent'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday paid tribute to a 'formidable opponent' whom he
liked and respected.
The prime minister's praise came as scores of tributes to John Smith were
offered by politicians of all parties and by figures from many areas of
public life.
The Queen sent a personal message of condolence to Mr Smith's widow,
Elizabeth.
British business figures issued generous tributes, recognising that Mr Smith
had sought a constructive relationship with the City and industry.
In Westminster there was widespread praise for the Labour leader's
integrity, his strong political convictions and his keen wit. Labour MPs
expressed the certainty that, had he lived, Mr Smith would have led the
party to win the next general election.
In a crowded and hushed Commons chamber, Mr Major spoke of his 'deep shock
and sadness' at Mr Smith's death. The former Labour leader was 'one of the
outstanding parliamentarians of modern politics'. He could 'shape and move'
the Commons, and knew exactly how and when to move from one mood to another
for maximum effect.
'These are formidable skills, they are rare skills,' said Mr Major. 'And
even for those against whom those skills were deployed, it is hard to bear
that we will never see or hear those skills in this House again.'
Mr Neil Kinnock, Mr Smith's predecessor as Labour leader, said he was
'desolated' by news of his death. He said his grief was mixed with anger:
'Anger that he has gone when his vitality and his value were so clear, anger
that he has been denied the chance to show the full scope of his great
talents in the highest office.'
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, also spoke of the 'injustice that
such a bright talent, so close to the point of fulfilment, has been so
cruelly lost to us all'.
Baroness Thatcher, the former prime minister, said Mr Smith had been an
outstanding leader of the opposition: 'His dignity, his mind, his solemnity
and his sense of humour made him ideal for the job.'
Several union leaders - with whom Mr Smith had not always enjoyed an easy
relationship - expressed deep sadness. Mr Alan Jinkinson, general secretary
of Unison, the UK's biggest union, said: 'The Labour party and the country
have suffered a huge and devastating loss.'
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, spoke of 'a
tragic loss for the whole country'.
Sir Michael Angus, president of the Confederation of British Industry, said
the business community would be 'very sad' at the death of such a 'talented
parliamentarian with whom it has enjoyed a friendly and constructive working
relationship'.
Mr Peter Morgan, director-general of the Institute of Directors, said: 'John
Smith was a very decent man and will be a loss to British politics. He
recognised the key role which business had to play if his policies were to
be fulfilled.'
</TEXT>
