<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Budget goes through
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration's Dollars 1,500bn (Pounds 1,027bn) budget for the
fiscal year starting in October emerged virtually unscathed from its first
run through Congress when the Senate approved it by a 53-46 vote, Jurek
Martin writes.
Early passage by both houses stands in sharp contrast to last summer's
dramas, when it squeaked through by one vote in each chamber. Senator Jim
Sasser, budget committee chairman, attributed this to the public perception
that real economic progress was being achieved.
The budget, with a projected deficit of Dollars 175bn, sets broad spending
limits but leaves Congress free to change the mix.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
