<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / Bulgaria invests in N-plants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bulgaria's National Electricity Company is to invest a further Dollars 200m
(Pounds 134m) to upgrade and increase the safety of four Soviet-designed
440MW reactors at the troubled Kozloduy nuclear power complex. Kozloduy
provides 40 per cent of the country's power output and cannot be phased out
until alternative power sources are secured.
The National Electricity Company has already spent Dollars 50m on upgrading
the ageing power plants, which suffered from decades of poor maintenance and
from an exodus of skilled workers after the collapse of the communist
regime. Two of the four older reactors, dating from the 1960s, were declared
unsafe by international inspectors in 1991 and closed down for essential
repairs before they were re-opened last year.
The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development is managing and
co-ordinating an international fund for improving safety at Soviet-era
plants like Kozloduy, which is one of several nuclear power plants on the
Danube River. But western companies have been unwilling to play a full role
in upgrading such plants until complex legal issues are resolved in a way
which absolves them from responsibility for radiation and other inherited
environmental problems.
</TEXT>
