<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / IBM claims breakthrough in use of CDs to store data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Scientists in the US are claiming a breakthrough in recording technology
which makes it possible to store several movies, 12 hours of music or 1m
pages of printed text on a single compact disc.
The breakthrough could markedly influence the development of the
'multimedia' revolution which promises to deliver new, interactive varieties
of entertainment and information to television screens in the home and
office.
It could also revolutionise the storage and retrieval of business
information. At present, companies store regularly used information in
magnetic disc drives or 'jukeboxes' of optical compact discs.
The new technique, developed by researchers at International Business
Machines' Almaden research centre in San Jose, California, will multiply
tenfold the amount of data that can be stored in a given space. Any item can
be retrieved within 10 seconds, the researchers say.
Video games, training programmes and other multimedia applications should
benefit from the enhanced quality of image and sound made possible by the
IBM technique.
The essence of multimedia technology is the transformation of information of
all kinds - video images, music, text and so on - into the digital computer
language of bits and bytes in which it can be manipulated by computer and
transmitted over telecommunications lines.
Storage of bits is expensive. Optical disc technology, in which lasers
'read' marks on the metallised surface of a compact disc, has so far proved
the most cost-effective solution.
The IBM breakthrough has been to glue together individual discs without the
metal coating to form layered, three-dimensional stacks. Information
anywhere in the stack can be read by focusing the laser beam on the
appropriate layer. A 10-layer disc could store more than 1m pages of text.
One application could be the storage of millions of movies in digital form
for video-on-demand services. The new disc will not work in today's compact
disc drives, and multi-layer CDs will inevitably be more expensive to make
than single-layer discs.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>International Business Machines Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3652 Prerecorded Records and Tapes.
    P8731 Commercial Physical Research.
</IN>
