<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Devenish purchase helps Greenalls improve
to Pounds 29m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last year's acquisition of Devenish helped Greenalls Group, the pubs, drinks
and hotel operator, to a 13 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds 29m
in the six months to March 25, or 28 per cent before exceptionals.
Mr Peter Greenall, managing director, said 'not only have we delivered
synergies from the acquisition, but trading is above our expectations'.
Beer volume through the enlarged pub estate was down 4.8 per cent. However,
margins were helped by the renegotiation of brewing supply contracts, some
of which took effect within the half year. Profits from pubs, including the
effect of the acquisition, were up 47 per cent at Pounds 32.7m.
Profits from the Premier House range of pub restaurants, which Greenalls
plans as its main target for capital investment, were up 73 per cent at
Pounds 6m while those from UK hotels, the chief investment target in recent
years, were up 15 per cent at Pounds 8m.
Off-licence profits were down 11 per cent at Pounds 2m, as a result of
competition from supermarkets and cross-channel imports. However,
off-licence turnover had risen by 3 per cent since Christmas. Profits from
drinks and leisure were down 5 per cent at Pounds 2.4m.
On group sales up 21 per cent at Pounds 337m, operating profits rose 39 per
cent to Pounds 49.1m. Interest charges rose sharply to Pounds 16.5m (Pounds
9.6m). There were exceptional charges of Pounds 3.8m, consisting mainly of
Pounds 3.2m reorganisation costs in the drinks and leisure division,
involving 60 redundancies.
Earnings per share were up 3.6 per cent at 11.66p before exceptional items
and property profits, and down 7.8 per cent at 10.43p after them. The
interim dividend is raised 5 per cent to 5.334p.
Greenalls' shares closed 13p lower at 462p.
COMMENT
The market found these results slightly opaque, due to lack of information
on the Devenish contribution and uncertainty on the real progress in hotels.
In addition, the cash outflow of Pounds 45m in the half is slightly
unsettling. However, the pre-Devenish performance is claimed by the company
to be broadly represented by the 3.6 per cent rise in earnings per share. In
addition, the cash outflow should fall next year as investment on hotels
passes its peak. Assuming perhaps Pounds 84m pre-tax this year, the shares
are on some 15 times earnings. While this does not seem unduly expensive,
there is a discount due to uncertainty in a period of transition.
</TEXT>
