<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / General Motors to inject Dollars 10bn into pension fund
deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Motors yesterday took a significant step towards the reduction of
its serious pension fund deficit - by far the largest of any US corporation
 -when it agreed with government regulators that it would inject some
Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.8bn) of cash and stock into the scheme.
Investor concern about GM's unfunded pension liabilities, some Dollars
22.3bn at the end of 1993, has hung over the group's stock in spite of a
sharp improvement in operating profits.
The group announced last November that it was considering ameliorating its
pensions problem by contributing to its plans some Dollars 6bn-worth of GM
class E stock held by its treasury. The E stock represents a claim on the
dividend stream of Electronic Data Systems, GM's information technology
subsidiary.
GM said it had agreed with the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation, the
government agency which insures private-sector benefit plans, to contribute
177m Class E shares, worth Dollars 6.2bn at current market prices, and a
further Dollars 4bn in cash.
The recent rise in US interest rates - if sustained - will also sharply
reduce GM's deficit, as bond rates are used to calculate the company's
pension liabilities, and each 1 percentage point rise in bond yields cuts
the liability by some Dollars 5bn. US 30-year Treasury bond yields have
risen by well over 1 percentage point since the start of the year.
GM said yesterday that the Dollars 4bn cash contribution would come out of
cash flow. Under the deal with the PBGC, still subject to the approval of
the US Department of Labor, it must contribute at least Dollars 2bn at the
same time as the E shares and the balance no later than September 30, 1995.
When a company contributes to its pension fund above the annual minimum it
normally creates a credit balance which the company can use to reduce
pension contributions. GM has agreed to defer the use of these credits for
several years and will not be entirely free of the restraints until 2003.
Joint venture in India, Page 27
</TEXT>
