<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Shell first quarter steady at Pounds 949m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shell Transport and Trading, the world's largest integrated oil company,
yesterday reported a slight dip in first-quarter net profits to Pounds 949m
from Pounds 971m, as improvements in refining and marketing offset a steep
fall in exploration and production profits.
The results, calculated on a replacement cost of supplies basis, were
mid-range of analysts' forecasts. Shell shares closed down a penny at 741p.
Earnings per share were 10.3p, compared with 10.1p last time.
The Pounds 2.1bn cash flow from operations was flat compared with last year.
The financial strength of Shell was underscored by its low gearing of 17.6
per cent.
A 13 per cent rise in downstream profits to Pounds 488m (Pounds 431m) was
attributed to higher sales volumes and lower costs. The company said world
demand for oil products is stronger than last year. Oil product sales rose
worldwide, although downstream margins in Asia and Europe deteriorated
compared with the same period last year.
A 23 per cent fall in the crude oil price caused profits from exploration
and production to drop by 27 per cent, to Pounds 425m (Pounds 584m). But
average production of 1.83m barrels a day was 5.5 per cent up, as a result
of new fields coming onstream in the UK North Sea.
Shell's first-quarter profits are usually bolstered by high seasonal demand
for natural gas, a market segment in which the company has a strong
position. First-quarter sales volumes rose by 3.3 per cent to 7.17bn cubic
feet a day.
Chemicals returned to profit after three years of losses. First-quarter
profits were Pounds 56m, compared with a Pounds 22m loss last time.
The company attributed much of the improvement to restructuring initiatives,
but it also confirmed that demand for chemicals is recovering as growth
returns to western economies.
Shell has about 13 per cent of its capital employed in the chemical sector,
according to London brokers Societe Generale Strauss Turnbull, and would
there-fore benefit significantly from any strong upturn in demand.
But the company said the outlook for the sector was dependent on the pace of
economic recovery in Europe, where there is chronic over-capacity.
