<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Sainsbury posts rise in underlying profits: Charges and
reorganisation at UK's largest grocery retailer halve reported figure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J. Sainsbury, the UK's largest grocery retailer, shrugged off the gloom that
beset its January trading statement to announce an increase in underlying
profits, and a stabilisation of gross margins after the price skirmishing of
recent months.
Its reported pre-tax profit, on an FRS 3 basis, was halved from Pounds
732.8m to Pounds 368.8m, after charges of Pounds 38.7m following its
decision to begin depreciating buildings; a Pounds 341.5m property
write-down; and Pounds 28m reorganisation and redundancy costs at head
office.
Stripping out those items, however, pre-tax profits would have increased 6
per cent to Pounds 777m - including a Pounds 7m property gain - beating
Sainsbury's forecast in January of a 'small increase'.
Mr David Sainsbury, chairman, said gross margins fell 0.4 percentage points
in the second half - a result of the 'Essential for essentials' campaign,
involving price cuts on 300 own-label products.
He added: 'Although the competitive environment is still very tough, we
currently expect gross margins to be maintained at around their present
level.'
His comments failed to convince the stockmarket, however, with Sainsbury's
shares falling 3p to 388 1/2 p.
Mr Sainsbury said the price competition had been triggered not by surplus
space in the grocery market but by rivals Asda and Gateway cutting prices.
That had led to a repositioning of margins, but would not escalate into an
all-out price war.
After a slow start, he added, the 'Essentials' campaign had delivered volume
increases averaging 20 per cent on featured products.
Group sales for the year to March 12 rose 9.3 per cent to Pounds 11.2bn.
Sales in Sainsbury's supermarkets increased 7.1 per cent, with new space
contributing 6.5 percentage points. After inflation of 1.5 per cent,
like-for-like sales fell 0.9 per cent overall. Operating profits grew only
2.3 per cent to Pounds 732.2m, reflecting the lower margins.
The Savacentre hypermarkets lifted sales 8.1 per cent to Pounds 659m, and
trading profits 11.8 per cent to Pounds 40.6m. Sainsbury's Homebase, the DIY
chain, saw total sales increase 16 per cent to Pounds 328m, with operating
profits up 34.3 per cent to Pounds 23.9m.
In the US, sales at Shaws supermarkets grew 6.7 per cent to Dollars 1.9bn
(Pounds 1.3bn) and profits almost 50 per cent to Dollars 46.5m.
Mr Sainsbury said the group would consider further acquisitions in the US,
and would reduce the proportion of capital spending on its UK supermarket
chain in favour of the other businesses.
Earnings per share, after exceptionals, fell from 28.5p to 8p, but the final
dividend increased from 7.3p to 7.6p, lifting the total 6 per cent to 10.6p.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
