<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The thought of Joanna Lumley in the character of Kate Swift from Class Act
working as the world's bolshiest waitress in order to get the low-down in a
war between rival chefs is an attractive one. Having seen scorn and
super-ciliousness from Lumley in AbFab we know just how effective she can be
(9.00 ITV).
Anyone who has worked in a hospital knows that there really does seem to be
an odd association between the incidence of death and the sex drive of the
staff. An instinct to keep population figures steady? Who knows, but Cardiac
Arrest is the first hospital series I have seen which captures the frenetic
atmosphere (9.30 BBC1). The BBC2 series True Brits tells 'The Ambassador's
Story'. David Gore-Booth leaves the Foreign Office to take up his new post
as ambassador to Saudi Arabia and the programme records his meetings with
Salman Rushdie and the Queen (9.30). Crimewatch UK screens its 100th
edition, its proponents still arguing that its help in solving certain
crimes somehow justifies thoroughly nasty re-enactments of often violent
incidents (10.00 BBC1).
</TEXT>
