<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Fears on government competence cloud sales rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNY LUESBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The proportion of business leaders reporting increased sales volumes and
profits rose sharply last month, but their optimism about the economy fell,
largely as a result of political uncertainty.
In the Institute of Directors' bi-monthly survey of business opinion, based
on some 300 interviews, 70 per cent of directors reported an increase in the
volume of their company's business compared with six months earlier - up
from 61 per cent in February.
There was also a rise in directors reporting increased profits, to 59 per
cent in April from 52 per cent in February.
However, the balance of directors more optimistic about the economy over
those less optimistic fell to 33 percentage points in April, from 38 points
in February.
Twenty-four per cent - the biggest single group - of those who were less
optimistic cited government incompetence as their main reason. A further 15
per cent pointed to lack of demand, and 9 per cent to tax increases.
Of those who were more optimistic, mainly as a result of increased economic
activity, 6 per cent said factors such as political uncertainty and
government incompetence had restrained their optimism.
Thirty-four per cent said the April tax increases had made them less
optimistic about the UK economy and only 2 per cent said they had made them
more optimistic.
Fifty-eight per cent of directors in the north, 63 per cent in the Midlands
and 64 per cent in the south reported greater optimism about their own
companies' prospects.
Greatest confidence was reported in the services sector, where 72 per cent
of directors were more optimistic, followed by distribution, at 70 per cent,
and business services, at 62 per cent. In mining and construction the
proportion of directors reporting greater optimism about their own company's
prospects fell from 69 per cent in February to 55 per cent in April.
The biggest increase in optimism was among directors of medium-size
companies, employing between 101 and 200 people. These companies were also
the most likely to take on new employees during the next six months, with 55
per cent expecting increased employment levels and none expecting to cut
jobs.
The overall proportion of companies expecting to take on new employees rose
to 44 per cent in April, from 37 per cent in February.
</TEXT>
