<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Tories confront Heseltine on mail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday faced
opposition from his backbenchers over plans to privatise the Post Office.
Mr Robert Hicks, Cornwall South East, said there was 'genuine apprehension'
that fundamental changes to the Post Office could affect the sub-post office
network and the Royal Mail's uniform charge.
Sir Donald Thompson, Calder Valley, voiced his concern about the effects of
privatisation on rural post offices, many of which rely on a subsidy from
the Post Office.
Mr Hugh Dykes, Harrow East, said previous privatisations had been of
companies that had been by and large unsuccessful and lossmaking.
'In this case that is not so, and provided the Post Office can be freed from
Treasury bondage . . . there is no need to have the upheaval you have in
mind.'
Mr Heseltine, who favours privatisation of Royal Mail and the parcels arm,
said that a flotation would not affect the universality of delivery and the
universal charge for letters.
He pointed out that a significant competitor to the Post Office - the Dutch
Post Office - was about to have its shares floated and denied that previous
privatisations had only taken place because the companies had been in the
red.
'Privatisation has changed nationalised industries, serving a domestic
market from a monopoly base, to becoming competitive, world-class companies,
trading across the face of the earth to the greater benefit of the British
economy,' he said.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, attempted to reassure
backbenchers that the rural network of post offices would be safe
irrespective of privatisation.
Mr Colin Baker, general secretary of the Federation of Sub-Postmasters,
which represents 18,000 sub-postmasters, welcomed the speech.
However, Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, warned that post
offices were still under threat because they were prevented from expanding
their commercial activities.
</TEXT>
