<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Authorities shake-up could boost spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Local government reorganisation in England and Wales could bring a sharp
rise in spending and hamper managerial reforms, the Audit Commission warns
today.
In England and Wales the government plans to replace the current two-tier
system of counties and districts with new single-tier 'unitary' authorities,
based on amalgamations of districts, in 1996 and 1997. The commission, which
acts as a watchdog for the public sector, says this will be the most complex
local government reorganisation yet attempted.
But councils are not preparing for the change, it says, and some newly
created authorities 'could start life in a financial crisis, possibly
inheriting high spending commitments and low balances from outgoing
councils'.
'Outgoing' authorities, whose abolition is certain, may wish to enter into
'costly and long-term' commitments, unimpeded by any need for long-term
budgeting, according to the commission's report.
Figures for building new swimming pools - a local government responsibility
 -suggest that outgoing local authorities spent freely before the last
reorganisation to affect non-metropolitan England and Wales, in 1974.
In that year, 160 new swimming pools were opened, and more than 100 the next
year. But from 1977 to 1990, the number opened never exceeded 50.
The report says: 'The Audit Commission is aware that some councils facing
reorganisation are already planning to commission new projects.'
Reallocating needs-based government grants to the new councils could also be
expensive. Mr Bob Chilton, director of local government studies for the
commission, said grants to county councils were currently redistributive,
because they tended to spend equally across the areas they covered.
If smaller unitary authorities were created, needier districts would receive
more, while the wealthier areas would receive less, under the government's
formula. Mr Chilton suggested that the government might be forced to pay out
extra funds to reduce the effects on the 'loser' councils.
Compulsory competitive tendering of white-collar services could also be
damaged, and delayed. Mr Chilton said: 'There are two separate reform
processes which do not mesh.'
He said some authorities were using impending reorganisation as an excuse
not to prepare for the next round of tendering, which is scheduled to start
18 months after the new councils are formed.
More basic preparations are also lacking. By the end of last year, 40 per
cent of district and 30 per cent of counties had still failed to compile
full registers of council assets - supposed to be completed nine months
earlier.
Time for Change? Audit Commission. HMSO. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>RES  Capital expenditures.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-10140</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EELCZAB8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940512
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Low asset recovery rate expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The liquidators to the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International
expect to be able to realise only a third of the stated assets of its
English operations, an official report revealed yesterday, Andrew Jack
writes.
Touche Ross, the accountancy firm, said it had realised Dollars 749.6m
(Pounds 513.4m) and estimated that a further Dollars 344.2m could be
recovered from a book value of Dollars 3.2bn, according to the annual return
filed with the Department of Trade and Industry.
The low proportion gives an indication of the poor degree of loan management
or the extent of falsification in the figures reported in BCCI's accounts in
the final year before it was closed in a worldwide swoop by regulators in
July 1991.
Total receipts in the English liquidation to January 15 this year are
Dollars 882.4m, including Dollars 132.8m in interest and tax refunds.
Most of the realisations are from the BCCI loan book - with a reported value
of Dollars 1.7bn - which included more than 63,000 overdrawn accounts.
The DTI report shows that there have been 34,799 claims on the English BCCI
branch assets from creditors around the world totalling Dollars 3.17bn.
BCCI in Liquidation. Report to the Secretary of State for Trade and
Industry. Touche Ross, 100 Leadenhall St, London EC3A 3AD. Free.
</TEXT>
