<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Sunday betting go-ahead welcomed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bookmakers yesterday expressed delight at the decision to allow Sunday
betting on horse-racing in England and Wales, but warned that the industry
faced strong competition from rival attractions such as do-it-yourself
stores and garden centres.
The Commons approved Sunday betting by a majority of 101 on Tuesday night.
Evening betting, which began last year, has provided a substantial boost to
bookmakers, which now hope Sunday racing will do the same.
William Hill, the second biggest bookmaking chain with 1,700 shops, said the
horse-racing industry would have to introduce new enthusiasts to the sport
rather than simply moving weekday customers to Sundays.
William Hill said it was not yet clear whether there would be a net increase
in race meetings or whether existing fixtures would be moved to Sundays.
It is too late to organise betting on Sunday racing this year. Next year
bookmakers expect about 12 meetings to take place on Sundays, and say the
real effect will not be felt until 1996.
A small number of Sunday races without betting have been taking place since
1992. Mr Chris Bell, assistant managing director of Ladbroke Racing, said
these have demonstrated that it will be possible to bring new customers to
horse racing and betting.
Mr Bell, whose company is the biggest bookmaking chain with 1,923 shops,
said spectators at Sunday events had been different from those attending
races on other days - there had been significantly more families and
children.
He warned, however, that Sunday was already the main family leisure day. 'We
will have to compete with the rest of the leisure industry. The primary
opposition will be do-it-yourself, garden centres, pubs and time with the
family.'
Mr John Morgan, managing director of Coral Racing, said he expected the
racing industry to add other attractions to their events, as has happened in
other countries with Sunday racing. These could include shopping outlets and
parachute jumps.
</TEXT>
