<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Fingerprint decision near
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY and ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Home Office is close to deciding on the final shortlist of companies to
implement the first comprehensive national automated fingerprint recognition
system.
The system, which will cost Pounds 45m at present prices, will be used by
the 43 police forces in England and Wales.
The 18 tenderers have been reduced to 10 - Arvin Calspan, Digital Equipment,
Electronic Data Systems, International Business Machines, SAIC, TRW and
Unisys of the US, Groupe Bull of France, ICL, owned by Fujitsu of Japan, and
Siemens Nixdorf of Germany.
On Monday the list will be reduced to four and a final decision will be made
in October for the system, which will be introduced in three years.
A number of police forces are already making use of an IBM automated
fingerprint recognition service.
The intention is that the new system will for the first time combine
identification of fingerprints discovered at the scene of a crime and
personal identification - comparing a suspect's prints with those held on
the database.
</TEXT>
