<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Thefts of trucks 'cost Pounds 500m'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Truck theft costs British industry more than Pounds 500m a year, the Freight
Transport Association said yesterday. More than one in three operators had a
vehicle stolen last year.
An association survey of 1,200 companies found that security devices
generally had only a limited effect on the numbers of thefts. One company
reported 107 vehicles broken into or stolen.
Some companies found novel ways of beating the thieves: one painted its
vehicles bright pink, and another carried raw sewage.
The survey found that 45 per cent of vehicles stolen were fitted with
alarms; nearly half the thefts took place at home depots; and that most
thefts were in the north-east of England with London, Birmingham and Bristol
being other badly hit areas, and Scotland the most theft-free area.
</TEXT>
