<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / De-regulation post demands rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government last night rejected demands that an opposition MP should head
the new Commons committee which is to scrutinise a faster procedure for
repealing legislation that imposes unnecessary burdens on commerce and
industry.
Mr Nick Brown, from the Labour front bench, and Mr Archie Kirkwood, for the
Liberal Democrats, maintained that the committee's stature would be enhanced
if its chairman were appointed from the opposition benches.
The new committee, composed of 16 MPs, will examine proposals by ministers
to use powers provided by the de-regulation bill to remove redundant acts
from the statute book by parliamentary orders instead of through new primary
legislation.
Mr Brown said he feared that the de-regulation bill would be used to remove
important legislative safeguards ensuring essential safety standards for
workers, and promised that it would be repealed by the next Labour
government.
Sir Peter Emery, Tory chairman of the procedure committee, said the
de-regulation scrutiny committee would have sufficient power to alert the
Commons if there was any possibility of the new powers provided by the bill
being abused.
Mr George Galloway, Labour MP for Glasgow Hillhead, warned that a
'Conservative placeman' would be appointed to chair the new committee, and
that the committee would provide no real protection whatever.
</TEXT>
