<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / Expenses come under tax reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies will be required to provide employees with details of their
expenses and benefits-in-kind each year under proposals for the new tax
system of self-assessment unveiled yesterday by the Inland Revenue.
They will have to provide full information to staff on pay and tax deducted
by May 19 after the end of the tax year, and submit expenses and benefits
information by July 6.
The details are contained in a consultative document on the implications of
self-assessment for employers and employees just circulated.
Self-assessment, which begins in the 1996-97 tax year, will affect an
estimated 9m taxpayers who submit tax returns, including many in the
Pay-As-You-Earn (PAYE) system in the upper-rate tax band or with complex tax
affairs.
The system was proposed in 1991, ratified by the last two chancellors, and
many of the details were passed in the most recent finance act which became
law last month.
The focus so far has been on the self-employed, but the latest proposals
provide further details for those on PAYE who will still be ensnared by the
new system.
The Revenue recommends that the employer should include information on the
cash equivalent for any benefit-in-kind provided to the employee. Companies
would face fines if they fail to provide employees with the information.
Comments on the document are invited by July.
</TEXT>
