<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Israeli deal given to Bell team
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An investment consortium led by Bell South of the US yesterday won Israel's
public tender to provide nationwide cellular phone services.
It was in competition with Motorola-Bezek, the Israel state-owned telephone
company, which had a monopoly till now.
The entry of a second player in the cellular phone market is part of the
Israeli government's ongoing liberalisation programme intended to encourage
efficiency and competition.
The communications ministry said the Bell South Consortium - which includes
the Safra family of bankers, Discount Investments of Israel, and Israel
Aircraft Industries - had won the tender because it had submitted the lowest
price customers will pay for services.
Israel expects the consortium to invest Dollars 85m (Pounds 57m) to Dollars
130m (Pounds 87m) in the expanding cellular phone market and to start
operating within 15 months.
The country has 60,000 cellular phone users and the communications ministry
predicts that the national market will increase to 350,000 within 10 years.
Motorola-Bezek's licence, which had been due to expire this year, was
extended until 2010 after the state-owned group had agreed to lose its
monopoly.
