<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 94 / US rejects 'new Haitian president'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The White House yesterday condemned the installation of a new president in
Haiti but denied reports that it had already decided to remove the Caribbean
republic's military junta by force, if tougher sanctions agreed last week by
the United Nations do not work.
US officials said, however, that some kind of UN security force, including a
significant US component, would be needed, even if the sanctions do force
out General Raoul Cedras and his colleagues.
Haitian legislators had named Supreme Court Justice Emile Jonassaint as
interim president. This is seen as further defiance by the military regime
and its associates of UN efforts to restore the exiled President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power.
'We expect him to return (to Haiti) at some point,' said a White House
official, calling the legislators' move 'cynical, unconstitutional and
illegal.'
The Haitian embassy in Washington said the installation of Justice
Jonassaint was 'designed to protect (the junta's) personal interests,
further increase the suffering of the Haitian people, and plunge the country
deeper into chaos.'
President Bill Clinton has been careful in recent statements not to rule out
the use of US military force to remove the junta that ousted Father Aristide
in 1991. However, US officials are anxious to give sanctions some time to
work.
'There has been no decision to send in a small force to purge the military,'
said Ms Madeleine Albright, US ambassador to the UN.
The sanctions are to go into effect if Gen Cedras and his colleagues have
not left Haiti by May 21. US officials declined to say how long they planned
to wait to see whether the sanctions work.
</TEXT>
